WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
This is how you can get started working with your data inside of your code environment.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:05.280
Step 1 is to pick your dataset.

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:07.160
You can grab data from a ton of different sources.

00:00:07.160 --> 00:00:11.160
A few common ones are from your local files, from any CSV that you've downloaded.

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:15.040
You can use API requests, which pulls live data from the web, or you can use some built-in

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:18.879
datasets from libraries like scikit-learn, seaborn, or huggingface.

00:00:18.879 --> 00:00:21.000
Step number 2 is to create a new script in your IDE.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:22.440
I always use positron.

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:24.959
Positron is built for data apps, so it is great for this sort of workflow.

00:00:24.959 --> 00:00:27.879
Open the app, click file, new file, and new python script.

00:00:27.879 --> 00:00:31.639
Then you can save the file in the same folder as your dataset if you're working locally.

00:00:31.639 --> 00:00:33.759
Then step 3 is to actually load the data.

00:00:33.759 --> 00:00:37.279
Once you've got it loaded into your notebook, you can use some common commands like df.head,

00:00:37.279 --> 00:00:40.959
df.info, or dataframe.describe to see some summary statistics.

00:00:40.959 --> 00:00:43.840
Whatever project you plan to work on, model training, dashboards, or just playing with

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:47.720
data, step 1 is always getting it into your environment, and positron makes that such

00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:48.720
a smooth experience.

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:51.840
Make sure you leave any questions in the comments below and follow along for more data science

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:52.840
content.

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:52.840


